Author: m.i8622
Content: I completely agree.  Education, gender equality, and freedom of expression have all been affected by the growing influence of conservative religious and traditional values, particularly when they become politicised.  It has an impact on young people's creativity, dreams, and ways of thinking.  Rather of progressing alongside the rest of the world, we are stuck in cycles of censorship and moral policing.  The fear of being perceived as "un-Islamic" or "disrespectful to tradition" is strangling Indonesia's potential.  It's about making room for different viewpoints to develop, not about denying faith.

Content:
im a girl and probs gonna get hate or whatever for saying this but hot take: feminism isnt about and we should lessen the  ‚Äúi hate men‚Äù ‚Äúmen should be put in jail before being released in the society‚Äùbut rather helping them fix their emotional problems. 

i get tho for years and centuries men have been in the centre of bad thing however, im beginning to think that this constant cycle of "I hate men lol" posts is simply a low-level indulgence that goes nowhere. It's similar to screaming at a brick wall and hoping it will improve itself. 

this the agreement: The majority of males are not sinister geniuses. they are chronically deprived of validation, emotionally inhibited, and have been taught from a young age that being vulnerable is a sign of weakness and being dominant is a sign of strength. 

unprocessed grief, anxiety, self hatred, and fear repackaged as ego, silence, or violence is what we frequently refer to as "toxic masculinity." 

perhaps we should channel our anger instead of making memes out of it and not for them, but for us and men must be held accountable if we want healthier relationships, safer communities, and better sons. however, they also require therapy, emotional literacy, and practical advice on how to improve as people. 
endlessly mocking them for not knowing how to feel and then getting angry when they lash out or implode is just lazy activism. 

men shouldn't be hated but they should be made to connect with their inner child who wasn't permitted to weep. 
That's the true revolution ‚ù§Ô∏è

Content:
Saw your IG story on weed legalisation but i just wanna tell my personal experience with it while im pro legalisation on weed but doing it on public is getting out of hand where i am at the moment and the war on drugs was never really about drugs, and people should absolutely have the freedom to use cannabis without fear of arrest. Legalisation brings safer products, less criminalisation, and more tax revenue no argument there.

but here‚Äôs the thing: just because it‚Äôs legal doesn‚Äôt mean i want to inhale it everywhere i go.

living in a place where people can smoke freely in public, i‚Äôve realised the reality isn‚Äôt as chill as it sounds. the smell is intense it clings to clothes, hair, and lingers long after the joint is gone. It‚Äôs like cigarette smoke, but stronger and harder to escape. Getting on a bus next to someone who just lit up is annoying and plus there can be kids and elderly that can be sensitive to it and worse it gives me migraines the and it‚Äôs not-about being anti-weed its about not being forced to experience someone else‚Äôs high just by existing in the same space.

wedon‚Äôt allow open alcohol on public transport or cigarettes in indoor spaces anymore, so why is public weed smoking treated differently?

legal doesn‚Äôt mean anywhere, anytime and it‚Äôs  time we talk about basic etiquette or designated smoking areas bcs enjoying weed shouldn‚Äôt come at the cost of everyone else‚Äôs comfort ‚Äî or health.

We‚Äôve legalised weed. Cool. Now let‚Äôs legalise some courtesy. @G CAT (Indah G)

Author: quetietrep7537
Content:
more tax revenue from weed is a horrible idea
i think we cant assume the good things of safer products and decriminalization without a coherent plan and a well thought out program
legalising something that is this easily diverted and clandestinely produced only on selected specific use cases (that we know wont be accessible anyways like the rest of the healthcare system) opens up a parallel legal and illegal ecosystem
when taxation is involved the war on drugs will evolve according to this new ecosystem
even in places of total prohibition, the war on drugs (or honestly any type of criminality with the opportunity to be organised) revolves around untaxed criminal income
in places like canada people will buy untaxed ilicit adulterated weed because they are motivated to both by legitimate and whatever you think are illegitimate reasons
they will ultimately be criminalised over taxes regardless if the reasons are considered legit or they wont be even if its "pointless" recreation just because its taxed from a legal dispensary

my pedes take is rather than limited legalisation there should be a pilot program of totally decriminalisation of small scale production for personal use to deconflict definitions of users and traffickers (learning from brazil) and limit accumulation (some of yall modern in mind but really still feudal in practice)
paired with public health and agricultural engagement there should be an improvement in safe practices (like sex) and improvement of reliance on self over illicit sources (also like sex)
also you wont have a war over tax avoiding money laundering cartels bc no one would buy from them and theyd rather diversify towards other more profitable activities

Content: euros 2025 was just ending yesterday and im a woman and I still think women‚Äôs football isn‚Äôt going to take off and forcing visibility doesn‚Äôt create genuine demand. Not everything needs to be equal in popularity and that‚Äôs okay ü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è

Author: floatingtales
Content:
yeah forcing visibility isn't the solution but man, it does need to be visible so that it will have at least a good foundation for paying these women athletes.

Like man, WNBA is constantly in the red and has to be funded by the NBA. This will reflect in the players' pay. Male athletes can get contracts of up to millions of dollars, while women players are lucky if they hit 6 digits.

I'd even hazard a guess that the least paid player in the NBA is still paid comfortably more than the most paid player in the WNBA.

Author: svgarfed
Content:
The interest just isn‚Äôt there and the average WNBA game draws under 500K viewers, while NBA games average over 1.6 million. Sponsorship and pay follow audience, not ideals. 

Until there‚Äôs a genuinely engaged audience, not just a politically correct one, the money won‚Äôt match and neither will the salaries. Visibility is helpful, but it‚Äôs not a substitute for actual demand

Author: pompompuringdom
Content: how do y‚Äôall reckon they can actually ORGANICALLY increase visibility for women‚Äôs sports?

Author: floatingtales
Content:
If we were to look at the inverse: there are sports where women draws more viewers than men. Stuff like Gymnastics, Synchronized Swimming, Figure Skating women perform significantly at a high level, perhaps at an ability that's equal to, or superior to men. So what I'm thinking is: people are drawn to high levels of performance and quality. To get them to watch women sports, it would need to be of high quality, perhaps comparable to men's sports. To do so, it is paramount to support women should they want to pursue sport.

But this is a chicken/egg debate here, because most of the women will not want to do sport just for the love of the game, they need it to be a level of profitable as well, being a female sports athlete might not be good financially career wise, leading to less people and less talent pool, leading to less sponsorships, less pay, and lessening the pool more and more. Inversely, if there are a lot of people who want to be an athlete, and continuously improve their craft, it will draw more eyes, and it will result in more sponsorships, leading to higher pay, which leads to more people wanting to be athletes.

Author: gabeauf
Content:
About Nepal, I'm so really careful. I'm not sure it's really a Revolution for me. The "Revolution" is not mean always good for people.
A problem about GenZ, this demonstration was supported by America and other western imperialism.

I am very sceptical about the appointment of the new Prime Minister. Just because she is a woman does not mean that this is progress. I am sceptical about her real fight against corruption. I do not deny that corruption exists, but where does it come from? Her appointment has been welcomed by the European Union in order to maintain its European imperialist power. His appointment was also welcomed by India's far right. The US approves of the same thing. The more I learn, the more I see that Gen Z has been well funded by pro-Western organisations to disrupt the legacy of the Nepalese revolution that took place between 1995 and 2008.

Nepal is a buffer state between China and the US in terms of geopolitical tensions. Oli, the outgoing Prime Minister, is known for his pro-China stance, as he knows he cannot rely on imperialist powers to bring national projects to fruition. Oli is renowned for opposing the Indian threat. The Indian government advocates Hindu supremacy and hegemony. 

This is not the first time that the NEP or the CIA have financed chaos and false revolutions to overthrow governments that oppose imperialism and Western powers.

That's why it's not possible to compare Nepal with Indonesia for example.

Author: gabeauf
Content: That's a fact, Indonesia, It is a semi-colonial and semi-feudal country, serving the capitalist interests of imperialist powers, mainly the USA. This is what your country has been suffering since the era of Suharto, who overthrew Sukarno, the father of Indonesian independence. It is sad to see how Indonesia still bears heavy scars, heavy consequences of Suharto's policies, which severely persecuted Indonesian Chinese, Christians, moderate Muslims, the vast majority of communists, Hindus, and more broadly, non-Muslims. The massacre of 1965‚Äì1966 is truly abominable and terrifying. When I see how people were targeted, it is almost genocide. Other ethnic and religious minorities too. Especially when you consider how incredibly rich Indonesia is in terms of ethnic diversity. This country deserves better, deserves to evolve in a positive way, with the fight against poverty, tolerance of diversity and modernity that benefits both the population and nature. In my opinion, it is truly one of the most beautiful and incredible multi-ethnic countries, along with China, Vietnam and India. There are also other multi-ethnic countries, which I have probably forgotten.

Author: pompompuringdom

Author: gabeauf
Content:
I think we greatly underestimate the power of American imperialism and its influence around the world... It's a truth that we can't always accept because we've been sold the falsehoods of the American dream, as the so-called land of freedom, but it's completely the opposite. When you see the dark side of the US during the Cold War, it's frankly horrible.

Honestly, I would have liked to talk about politics without mentioning American imperialism, as a kind of break, haha. It's clear that it's difficult to accept the facts when you've been swayed by powerful propaganda, which is everywhere: films, books, television series, all presenting a beautiful illusion of Western democracy...

I find it sad that I am regularly labelled a conspiracy theorist when I mention American imperialism and its role in foreign interference to maintain its geopolitical influence around the world. It's mind-boggling...

I can talk really French imperialism. If we want to talk politics and what's happening in many African countries, I can easily discuss French and British imperialism. No worries :D. In fact, talking about Africa, the continent and its politics, is a good way to forget about American imperialism by focusing on British and French imperialism. Hahahaha !

Btw, I feel you, sometimes, I'm asking, it's possible to talk about any political issue without to tell american western imperialism ?

Author: gabeauf
Content: I think it has become an obsession to talk about American and Western imperialism, because it is greatly underestimated and we can clearly see the consequences, the inequalities between countries in the North and countries in the South. It's horrible. I am even reading a book called Imperialism in the 21st Century, in French. What I am learning is that it is revolting and that we really need to take an interest in anti-imperialism in order to wage more intelligent struggles throughout the world. When the American proletariat finally takes an anti-imperialist stance, and the Europeans do too, the world will finally change and we will experience new prosperity, peace and equality.

Author: sashaaanandini
Content:
I kinda agree with @angeryshibe comment.
It's hard to socialize with someone with lower social/economic class mainly because sometimes it's just a lil bit awkward. While I've never grew up rich (just comfortable enough I guess?) I do have some friends within the lower social/economic class than me and sometimes it would bug me when the blush over things I have and they couldn't. Even worse, I've had some that tried to take advantage of me financially.

On the flip side, I also have some friends/family members that's richer than me and I'd have to admit that sometimes I envy them or just think that they're so comfortable with their finance situations that they don't really care about the money value whereas I'd have to think about every single expense.

**TL;DR** 
Most of the times our financial situations, especially the one we grew up in, will effect our social life too. There are things that we are so used to and couldn't imagine how other people survive without it, and it goes both ways, we'd wonder why some people would need things in their life that we see as unnecessary. Which is why some are more comfortable to mingle within their own social class.

Author: m.i8622
Content:
You can love AI and care about the planet. what i mean is we don‚Äôt stop making art because paper takes trees ‚Äî we just get smarter about how we create. The answer isn‚Äôt ‚Äúdon‚Äôt use tech,‚Äù it‚Äôs ‚Äúuse it consciously.‚Äù Guilt doesn‚Äôt change the world, innovation does

It‚Äôs true that AI systems (like most tech) use energy and resources ‚Äî data centers do consume a lot of electricity and water for cooling. But that doesn‚Äôt mean using AI makes you a bad person or hypocritical. It‚Äôs the same as liking air conditioning, streaming movies, or using your phone ‚Äî all of which also have environmental costs.

The key is being aware of the impact, not guilt-tripping yourself for using tools that genuinely help or inspire you. You can appreciate the convenience or creativity AI gives you and still care about sustainability ‚Äî those two things can coexist
